column8:
We have a long history of success in the small to mid cap value part of the market with an experienced and talented team of analysts, and our accumulated institutional knowledge is a true asset. As we have been reflecting on the environment, it has become clearer to us that investors want increasingly idiosyncratic investments that are well researched and risk managed. Therefore, we are strengthening our efforts in the small to mid cap value part of the market where our fundamental approach leads us to differentiated, undiscovered, and misunderstood opportunities.

As part of this process, we have made a determined effort to reduce the number of companies in which we are invested firm wide. We have made good progress and it is a continual process. We want to leverage our best ideas and by focusing on fewer names, it becomes a virtuous process of having the time and resources to develop the conviction to hold securities in larger weightings. Each strategy has reduced its total number of holdings and concentration continues to increase in the top half of the portfolios.

We are also enthusiastic about our Long/Short Equity strategy as it leverages our core capabilities in structuring a highly differentiated and concentrated portfolio with low correlation and strong risk management characteristics.

Since our founding in 1988, BlackRock’s core philosophy has been grounded in the belief that experienced investment professionals using a disciplined process and sophisticated analytical tools can consistently add value to client portfolios. With this as a framework, BlackRock has assembled teams of investment professionals with significant expertise in global capital markets. Through BlackRock Solutions, we continue to invest substantial resources to the ongoing development of our technology and analytic capabilities, for both internal users and BlackRock Solutions clients. Our focus on investment excellence and advanced proprietary analytics is complemented by an unwavering, senior-level commitment to service, resulting in dynamic client relationships and enabling us to assist clients with all aspects of their investment needs.
 
In light of the size, scope, and expanded global perspective of BlackRock, a consistent, interconnected “one BlackRock” approach is vital.

Mission Statement
Our mission is to create a better financial future for our clients. As we pursue that mission, we are guided by our culture and a set of principles that ensure we never forget what we stand for.
 
We are a Fiduciary to Our Clients. Their interests come first—always. We speak with the courage of our convictions. We say what we do and do what we say. We have a responsibility to be the voice of the investor, and we represent each client fairly and equally.
 
We are Passionate about Performance. We are passionate about our work and intensely focused on performing at the highest levels. Our success requires that we out-think and out-work our competitors. We prize strong subject matter expertise and an insatiable appetite to learn.
 
We are One BlackRock. We know that the best solutions result from the ideas and contributions of a diverse team of partners. Diversity strengthens us and delivers better results for our clients. We expect our employees to have a strong working knowledge of the firm beyond their core responsibilities. Constant communication is critical to our success.
 
We are Innovators. Continuous innovation helps us bring the best of BlackRock to our clients. Innovation requires us to be respectfully anti-bureaucratic, to challenge the status quo and not be afraid of failure. We are proud of our long history of innovation, and that history of introducing new and innovative approaches across our entire business has been the foundation of our success.

column8:
Founded in Europe, the firm moved its headquarters to New York City in 1937 but has always maintained a world-wide frame of reference. We are committed to nurturing an investment-centric culture with a long-term global perspective that reflects our extensive international business experience. We view ourselves as a firm of investors, not of asset-gatherers, and in the aggregate, the Arnhold family and key employees are the largest fee-paying investors across the First Eagle strategies. Our interests are closely aligned with those of our clients, and we measure success by the same standard: consistently strong long-term performance. 

First Eagle strives at all times to preserve the high standards that we have maintained over our 150-year history: a record of integrity, a work environment that fosters excellence and dedication, and the earned respect of our clients and our peers.

HCM makes money from good old-fashioned stock picking, not technical quantitative models (“black boxes”) or complicated credit bets. HCM’s stock ideas are centered on a relatively limited number of investment themes (typically 4-8) enabling the firm to be early identifiers of change (whether at a company, industry, sector, market or other level). We capitalize on the change by buying companies that will benefit and selling or going short companies that will be hurt from the change. 
 
Our primary goal is generating extraordinarily high rates of return. In the “no free lunch” world of investment management, high returns must come with higher levels of volatility. We view volatility as a two-sided coin – one side being “good” upside volatility (which most investors do not object to) and the other side being “bad” downside volatility (which most investors object to). What HCM has succeeded in doing is capturing a disproportionate share (historically better than 2:1) of the “good” over the “bad.” In investment parlance, HCM investors have in years past received a lot of “alpha” for some “beta.”
 
Because of HCM’s unique stock selection process (investment themes and use of hurdles, driven by a 30-year industry veteran), HCM’s investment returns generally have a low correlation to the market. Hence, by including HCM in its stable of managers (which often include passive managers), an investor may increase diversification and thus improve the risk-return profile of its total overall portfolio. We would encourage prospective investors to analyze whether including HCM in their stable of managers improves the risk-return profile of their entire portfolio. Also, HCM’s west coast location often affords us a unique investment perspective (resulting in portfolios not created with consensus thinking) and is another source of diversification when selecting investment managers.

column8:
Cognios offers both quantitative value and quantitative growth investment strategies. Our proprietary ROTA-ROME® investment philosophy and our approach to earnings + price acceleration are unique to Cognios as well as the associated quantitative methodologies that support them. Risk management processes are implemented through each stage of a strategy’s design and execution. 
All of Cognios’ investment strategies share a common investment approach:

1) Investment activities are data driven to minimize the impact of heuristics and biases that are inherent in human judgment and potentially detrimental to investment returns.
2) Investment strategies utilize a quantitative portfolio construction process that systematically identifies companies for the portfolio based on each strategy’s stated investment policy and objective. 
3) All strategies employ a bottom-up selection process and are built around valuation and/or growth factors that research, our own as well as academic & institutional, have shown result in outperformance over time.

At Martin Currie, strategic planning is oriented to the overall quality of the firm, with a primary focus on delivering investment excellence. Its aim as an active-equity manager is to deliver consistent, superior returns for clients globally. Martin Currie does this via its client focused range of outcome orientated equity investment solutions based on its four distinct product pillars, Market Aware, Long-Term Unconstrained, Sustainable Income and Growth and Absolute Returns. 

The delivery of investment excellence is central to what Martin Currie offers its clients. This means a clearly-articulated investment proposition: 
Committed to high-conviction active management
Martin Currie’s high-conviction, active management is driven by the rigour of its distinctive and repeatable research process. 
A collaborative and multi-disciplinary approach to research, drawing on the knowledge of colleagues from across the investment floor, enables Martin Currie to identify and evaluate the mispricing of individual stocks – specifically for those companies that it believes will offer sustainable, long-term growth. This in-house research is always complemented by local market research, lateral industry insights, and company meetings. 
Of course, this is not a process in isolation. It is interwoven with a strong valuation discipline based on the forecasting of normalised earnings power, as well as risk, to determine a company’s fair value.
ESG analysis and active ownership are also fully embedded into Martin Currie’s investment process. This allows Martin Currie to engage with investee companies in order to better understand what motivates them and the mechanisms in place for decision-making. 
Overlaying all of this is an independent and dynamic risk function that informs an optimum risk allocation. All portfolios are continuously monitored for correlated, unintended and excessive risk. When market conditions change, the investment risk team provides Martin Currie’s portfolio managers with experienced interpretation of risk models to quantify the likely impact. As such, Martin Currie thinks of its independent risk team as being the representative of its clients within the firm.
The responsibility for the creation and implementation of the firm’s plan sits with the executive committee, chaired by Chief Executive Officer, Julian Ide.

column8:
Diamond Capital Management relies heavily on selling or "writing" options on stock index futures. DCM may also, from time to time, purchase options and may employ the use of hedge strategies such as option spreads, straddles, strangles or may purchase or sell futures to offset an open option position. 

The profitability of a trading strategy consisting of selling ("writing") options on an index depends upon the subsequent price movement of the index. It is the intention of Diamond to write mainly "out-of-the-money" puts and calls while seeking to sell into volatility. Thus, if the index remains within the predetermined trading range and the option remains "out-of-the-money" until the position is closed or expires, the puts and/or calls will be profitable. 

Diamond’s trading strategy is not dependent on market moves and is therefore suited to all types of market conditions. For example, instead of seeking to profit through the purchase of individual shares of stock, which are in the benchmark S&P 500 Index, DCM sells options on the Index itself. When writing options on the S&P 500 Index, the market can move up, down, or sideways within a specific range and still produce profits at, or as it nears, option expiration. Conversely, when buying stocks, the stock must move higher and/or pay good dividends to make the trade profitable.

It is Diamond's goal to produce consistent positive returns with a maximum monthly drawdown of less than 5 percent not to exceed 10 percent during any consecutive monthly periods. Rigorous risk management is used to minimize monthly drawdown's. As such, the trading strategies have pre-defined profit goals and risk exposure. Stop loss measures are utilized as well as the use of derivative hedging techniques to quantify market exposure. 

Investment in this strategy is speculative and involves a high degree of risk. There can be no assurance that DCM’s investment objective will be achieved, and investment results may vary significantly year to year.

column8:
HCM makes money from good old-fashioned stock picking, not technical quantitative models (“black boxes”) or complicated credit bets. HCM’s stock ideas are centered on a relatively limited number of investment themes (typically 4-8) enabling the firm to be early identifiers of change (whether at a company, industry, sector, market or other level). We capitalize on the change by buying companies that will benefit and selling or going short companies that will be hurt from the change. 
 
Our primary goal is generating extraordinarily high rates of return. In the “no free lunch” world of investment management, high returns must come with higher levels of volatility. We view volatility as a two-sided coin – one side being “good” upside volatility (which most investors do not object to) and the other side being “bad” downside volatility (which most investors object to). What HCM has succeeded in doing is capturing a disproportionate share (historically better than 2:1) of the “good” over the “bad.” In investment parlance, HCM investors have in years past received a lot of “alpha” for some “beta.”
 
Because of HCM’s unique stock selection process (investment themes and use of hurdles, driven by a 30-year industry veteran), HCM’s investment returns generally have a low correlation to the market. Hence, by including HCM in its stable of managers (which often include passive managers), an investor may increase diversification and thus improve the risk-return profile of its total overall portfolio. We would encourage prospective investors to analyze whether including HCM in their stable of managers improves the risk-return profile of their entire portfolio. Also, HCM’s west coast location often affords us a unique investment perspective (resulting in portfolios not created with consensus thinking) and is another source of diversification when selecting investment managers.

Gaineswood intends to broaden from its current customer base that is concentrated among a few family offices to institutions and selected RIAs interested in sub-advisory. Although the firm has been managing money since 1996, it has had very limited marketing until about 2007. At about that time, Gaineswood established GIPS performance measurement, placed performance and characteristics information into a large number of databases, and began to market its services to institutions, family offices, and selected registered investment advisors (RIAs). The founder values performance of customer accounts highest among the firm’s objectives. With limited resources he has erred in favoring this over directing resources to competing needs with the exception of maintaining compliance and necessary systems for reporting, financial management, risk assessment, and employee retention. Gaineswood’s management successfully saw its AUM rise through this period. When it achieves a milestone of $100 million of AUM, it feels its interesting historical performance combined with the larger customer base will appeal to small and medium sized institutions. Its largest addition into a single account was $10 million in 2006, which accounted for a major percentage of total AUM. While Gaineswood would not rule out an addition of $50 million or more given this previous success, it is targeting additions of $10 million or lower presently. Given the firm’s products typically have an average market cap of slightly over $2 billion and very low trading turnover, capacity should be between $2 billion and $3 billion. The investment philosophy has been successfully applied to new areas previously, and there is no inherent reason why it would not be applicable to international or large cap sectors.

Janus Henderson Investors exists to help clients achieve their long-term financial goals. 
Formed in 2017 from the merger between Janus Capital Group and Henderson Global Investors, we are committed to adding value through active management. For us, active is more than our investment approach – it is the way we translate ideas into action, how we communicate our views and the partnerships we build in order to create the best outcomes for clients. 

There are three key principles that underpin the way we work with our clients: 
- We put our clients first 
- We act like an owner 
- We succeed as a team 

We take pride in what we do and care passionately about the quality of our products and the services we provide. While our investment managers have the flexibility to follow approaches best suited to their areas of expertise, overall our people come together as a team. This is reflected in our Knowledge. Shared ethos, which informs the dialogue across the business and drives our commitment to empowering clients to make better investment and business decisions. 

We are proud to offer a highly diversified range of products, harnessing the intellectual capital of some of the industry’s most innovative and formative thinkers from both the Janus Henderson investment teams as well as sub-advisors Perkins, INTECH and Geneva. Our expertise encompasses the major asset classes, we have investment teams situated around the world, and we serve institutional, intermediary and individual investors globally. We have $330.8 B in assets under management, more than 2,000 employees and offices in 27 cities worldwide*. Headquartered in London, we are an independent asset manager that is dual-listed on the New York Stock Exchange and the Australian Securities Exchange. 

*Combined pre-merger figures of Janus Capital Group and Henderson Global Investors, as of March 31, 2017.

At the company level, LGM will remain an investment management equity specialist, with a primary focus on Asian, GEM and Frontier Equity Markets. They do not plan to diversify into other areas of financial services or any other business activity outside their core competency.

As mentioned earlier, they have six core strategies: GEM, Asia, Asian Small Cap, Frontier, China and India. In due course they plan to add a GEM Small Cap capability. Their primary strategic objective continues to be to provide their existing clients with superior investment performance and strong client service. As investors they look for quality companies with sustainable business models and, understandably, their own ambition is to grow our business over the long term at a pace commensurate with their resources and market liquidity by expanding their existing high quality client base.

As far as client type is concerned, their main focus will continue to be institutional rather than direct retail and with broad geographic diversity. They consider all geographies - Europe, North America, the Middle East and Asia-Pacific - to be key growth areas for new clients.

Capacity is not an issue for LGM in the foreseeable future except for their Frontier Markets Strategy which is currently close to their pre-determined capacity of US$1bn. Any soft product close would be announced to all clients and pipeline investors at the same time, strategy asset flows would be monitored carefully, and no new marketing activities would be undertaken for the strategy. A hard close would mean that no further asset inflows would be accepted from any investors (existing or potential clients), in order to protect the interests of ongoing client relationships.

Clients may invest in their strategies either through a separate account or pooled/mutual fund vehicles such as LGM’s Irish domiciled UCIT IV funds. Please contact LGM for detailed information.

column8:
VanEck’s mission is to offer investors forward-looking, intelligently designed investment strategies that take advantage of targeted market opportunities. VanEck’s approach is to think outside the confines of financial markets as they exist today and identify what major historical trends – political and technological – will change the opportunity set of these markets. Being one of the first to offer investors access to international markets in 1955 set the tone for the Firm’s drive to identify and define investment trends.

VanEck’s story evolves with the early identification of asset classes and trends that went on to shape the investment management business: in 1968 with monetary policy and gold, in 1993 with China and emerging markets, and in 2006 with ETFs.

VanEck brings its best to clients through:

-Independence – a history of placing clients’ interests first in all market environments
-Insight – early identification of investment trends and asset classes that investors may be missing
-Accessibility – clients access to portfolio management teams and Firm resources
-Execution – market-tested portfolio management teams and well-designed processes

We focus on identifying the ‘true’ drivers of stock returns to build better valuation metrics, the most important of which is Network Value. The theory backing this was published in the FAJ, essentially the elemental drivers of stock price are related to earnings and liquidity. Importantly, it is by avoiding or underweighting extremely high liquidity and not by owning extreme illiquidity that we obtain value added. 
Second, we do not optimize to client benchmarks and so try to minimize tracking error risk, but instead maximize our expected excess return by optimizing to a reference portfolio (an index that we construct ourselves) that is more efficient – which means we do not ‘hug the benchmark’. 
Thirdly, we combine this with an investment factor trend signal that is dynamic in nature; in other words, different factors will matter at different points in time. This valuation metric is designed to capture mid to long-term investor behavior, which will generally shift through time. The ability to adjust to a variety of market conditions has allowed us to outperform through a variety of investor themes (e.g. deep value environment, strong growth theme, energy demand theme, risk aversion theme). We believe that adaptability will continue to be the cornerstone of our process and will allow us to add value in the foreseeable future, regardless of what investor themes surface. These two main valuation metrics have zero to negative correlation to each other, which makes them extremely attractive compliments, but the first of these two has, and is expected to add the most value.
Finally, we apply judgmental special situations work that complements our investment strategy and consistently adds value.

column8:
At Martin Currie, strategic planning is oriented to the overall quality of the firm, with a primary focus on delivering investment excellence. Its aim as an active-equity manager is to deliver consistent, superior returns for clients globally. Martin Currie does this via its client focused range of outcome orientated equity investment solutions based on its four distinct product pillars, Market Aware, Long-Term Unconstrained, Sustainable Income and Growth and Absolute Returns. 

The delivery of investment excellence is central to what Martin Currie offers its clients. This means a clearly-articulated investment proposition: 
Committed to high-conviction active management
Martin Currie’s high-conviction, active management is driven by the rigour of its distinctive and repeatable research process. 
A collaborative and multi-disciplinary approach to research, drawing on the knowledge of colleagues from across the investment floor, enables Martin Currie to identify and evaluate the mispricing of individual stocks – specifically for those companies that it believes will offer sustainable, long-term growth. This in-house research is always complemented by local market research, lateral industry insights, and company meetings. 
Of course, this is not a process in isolation. It is interwoven with a strong valuation discipline based on the forecasting of normalised earnings power, as well as risk, to determine a company’s fair value.
ESG analysis and active ownership are also fully embedded into Martin Currie’s investment process. This allows Martin Currie to engage with investee companies in order to better understand what motivates them and the mechanisms in place for decision-making. 
Overlaying all of this is an independent and dynamic risk function that informs an optimum risk allocation. All portfolios are continuously monitored for correlated, unintended and excessive risk. When market conditions change, the investment risk team provides Martin Currie’s portfolio managers with experienced interpretation of risk models to quantify the likely impact. As such, Martin Currie thinks of its independent risk team as being the representative of its clients within the firm.
The responsibility for the creation and implementation of the firm’s plan sits with the executive committee, chaired by Chief Executive Officer, Julian Ide.

Aletheia’s objective is to pursue a strategy of moderate but continuous growth. There are currently no limits or a set amount of total assets under management for the firm, and due to the very high-quality, large-cap nature of the investment strategies, there are no foreseeable capacity limits or other total AUM issues in the near- to medium-term future. The objective is always to consistently add value and, as a result, if it is determined that AUM in any of the products become a limiting factor in achieving excess returns, Aletheia will further evaluate capacity limits. Furthermore, Aletheia’s team approach to its investment management services, supported by the firm’s Client Service, Operational, Compliance and other personnel, offers tremendous leverage with regard to the management of Aletheia’s client portfolios. Additionally, portfolios within a given strategy (subject to client specific restrictions and constraints) are all managed to an active model portfolio, which enables substantial precision and efficiency during the implementation of investment and portfolio changes. 

Aletheia has no plans to be involved in any acquisitions either as a buyer or a seller, as the firm believes its independent and management-controlled structure is the most ideal structure through which to provide investment management services to our clients. However, Aletheia will thoughtfully consider new strategies as appropriate and may add additional strategies in the future or create new vehicles through which our clients can invest our strategies. Over the last several years, Aletheia has invested significantly in its business to enhance the firm’s ability to meet client needs and objectives. This has been evidenced in the past few years with outstanding additions to the Investment Management, Research, Client Service, Compliance, Finance and Operations staff, as well as significant investment in plant and equipment and IT and back-office support resources.

We have a long history of success in the small to mid cap value part of the market with an experienced and talented team of analysts, and our accumulated institutional knowledge is a true asset. As we have been reflecting on the environment, it has become clearer to us that investors want increasingly idiosyncratic investments that are well researched and risk managed. Therefore, we are strengthening our efforts in the small to mid cap value part of the market where our fundamental approach leads us to differentiated, undiscovered, and misunderstood opportunities.

As part of this process, we have made a determined effort to reduce the number of companies in which we are invested firm wide. We have made good progress and it is a continual process. We want to leverage our best ideas and by focusing on fewer names, it becomes a virtuous process of having the time and resources to develop the conviction to hold securities in larger weightings. Each strategy has reduced its total number of holdings and concentration continues to increase in the top half of the portfolios.

We are also enthusiastic about our Long/Short Equity strategy as it leverages our core capabilities in structuring a highly differentiated and concentrated portfolio with low correlation and strong risk management characteristics.

Since our founding in 1988, BlackRock’s core philosophy has been grounded in the belief that experienced investment professionals using a disciplined process and sophisticated analytical tools can consistently add value to client portfolios. With this as a framework, BlackRock has assembled teams of investment professionals with significant expertise in global capital markets. Through BlackRock Solutions, we continue to invest substantial resources to the ongoing development of our technology and analytic capabilities, for both internal users and BlackRock Solutions clients. Our focus on investment excellence and advanced proprietary analytics is complemented by an unwavering, senior-level commitment to service, resulting in dynamic client relationships and enabling us to assist clients with all aspects of their investment needs.
 
In light of the size, scope, and expanded global perspective of BlackRock, a consistent, interconnected “one BlackRock” approach is vital.

Mission Statement
Our mission is to create a better financial future for our clients. As we pursue that mission, we are guided by our culture and a set of principles that ensure we never forget what we stand for.
 
We are a Fiduciary to Our Clients. Their interests come first—always. We speak with the courage of our convictions. We say what we do and do what we say. We have a responsibility to be the voice of the investor, and we represent each client fairly and equally.
 
We are Passionate about Performance. We are passionate about our work and intensely focused on performing at the highest levels. Our success requires that we out-think and out-work our competitors. We prize strong subject matter expertise and an insatiable appetite to learn.
 
We are One BlackRock. We know that the best solutions result from the ideas and contributions of a diverse team of partners. Diversity strengthens us and delivers better results for our clients. We expect our employees to have a strong working knowledge of the firm beyond their core responsibilities. Constant communication is critical to our success.
 
We are Innovators. Continuous innovation helps us bring the best of BlackRock to our clients. Innovation requires us to be respectfully anti-bureaucratic, to challenge the status quo and not be afraid of failure. We are proud of our long history of innovation, and that history of introducing new and innovative approaches across our entire business has been the foundation of our success.

At Old West Management, LLC, we are committed to treating our investors as we ourselves would like to be treated. Aside from being the right thing to do, we believe that attracting a dedicated investor base provides a competitive advantage for us to enact our disciplined, long term, and often contrarian investment process.

Our focus is on investing in businesses run by management teams with large stock ownership, reasonable pay, and track records of successfully compounding shareholder value. Further, we seek to buy into such businesses at discounted prices that offer us an attractive forward return with limited risk of capital loss.

To begin, we are always willing to discuss our current holdings and the research process behind them. Just as we focus on investing with management teams who are heavily invested in their own companies, we want investors who expect the same of us. Of our current assets under management, principals and their families account for roughly 13% of capital.

column8: At ValueWorks we define value investing as buying the best-quality assets at the best possible prices. We like to think of ourselves as bargain hunters: it is our goal to pay only $0.50 to $0.75 for $1.00 worth of assets. We evaluate the component parts of a company, assigning each of its assets a dollar value that, when added together, comprises the underlying value of the company; if this is higher than the company’s stock price, we consider it an investment opportunity. Converting these principles into practice requires a sophisticated and consistent process. It entails extensive independent research, a high level of expertise—in appraising both assets and claims—and the discipline not to be led by emotions when market conditions are volatile.

We believe in taking an active approach to investment management, building portfolios with a high level of conviction, while carefully managing risk. We see opportunity when certain asset classes and market segments are less efficient than others, creating particularly fertile ground for active management. Our detailed research harvests alpha by bridging sound fundamentals with pricing inefficiencies, and our suite of actively managed strategies are managed to identify these exceptional opportunities.

Asset Management Fee Growth: New Business
Client Retention Rates: Existing Clients
Assets Under Management: Cash Flows 
Operating Leverage
Revenue per Full Time Employee
Staff Attrition Rates

column8:
Quotient Investors focuses on equity strategies and seeks to provide portfolios that have a risk and return profile that meets the targets of its clients. The firm’s expertise is on applying a bottom-up quantitative approach to find mis-priced securities across the broad market.
Stock selection is driven by Quotient's insights into the valuation of companies operating within an industry. The valuation models incorporate fundamental, ESG, technical, as well as value, growth and momentum factors from multiple categories including: 1) a firm's financial statements, 2) analyst's earnings and growth estimates, 3) price and trading volume information, 4) management actions such as share issuance/repurchase, debt issuance/retirement and changes in dividends, 5) unique financial data specific to the REIT industry, 6) environmental, social and governance characteristics, 7) valuation methods such as the Dividend Discount Model, and 8) trading data such as volume and bid/ask spreads. Quotient looks at this information both in terms of relative comparisons between companies in the same industry and trends over time. Quotient builds a unique model for each industry based on the price drivers that are predictive in that industry. In total, there is a unique valuation model for each of the 56 industries that the firm follows.

Rail-Splitter Capital regards fundamental business analysis and individual stock selection as its primary strength. Consequently, the Fund’s performance is expected to be driven largely by stock selection, rather than from timing the market or macroeconomic analysis. The Fund’s long and short investments are concentrated in sectors and businesses where the firm’s analysts have extensive experience, expertise and information sources. 
We believe the best long-term investments are found in companies capable of sustained periods of value creation, as reflected in multiple years of superior earnings growth and returns on invested capital. Such performance typically reflects significant and sustainable competitive advantage. In our experience, this advantage is the product of strong management teams operating within attractive industry environments, often building upon strong brand franchises, leading market positions or proprietary business processes or technologies. We believe our principals and analysts are adept at identifying these qualities, and in determining their value. 
Rail-Splitter Capital seeks to invest the Fund’s assets in the equities of such value-creating companies, attempting to purchase them at advantageous prices. While a variety of valuation methodologies are considered depending on the company/sector under review, we generally prefer cash-earnings based valuation approaches. Investments are typically maintained until either (i) valuation appreciates beyond its estimation of fair value, (ii) some adverse change occurs in the business fundamentals, or (iii) the risk/reward inherent in an existing position is deemed inferior to a new investment idea. This approach has often led to long holdings exceeding the one year threshold for long-term capital gains treatment. However, the Fund also capitalizes on the analyst’s expertise regarding these companies by adjusting the size of core holdings or opportunistically entering into positions with shorter expected time horizons.

Such performance typically reflects significant and sustainable competitive advantage. In our experience, this advantage is the product of strong management teams operating within attractive industry environments, often building upon strong brand franchises, leading market positions or proprietary business processes or technologies. We believe our principals and analysts are adept at identifying these qualities, and in determining their value. 
Rail-Splitter Capital seeks to invest the Fund’s assets in the equities of such value-creating companies, attempting to purchase them at advantageous prices. While a variety of valuation methodologies are considered depending on the company/sector under review, we generally prefer cash-earnings based valuation approaches. Investments are typically maintained until either (i) valuation appreciates beyond its estimation of fair value, (ii) some adverse change occurs in the business fundamentals, or (iii) the risk/reward inherent in an existing position is deemed inferior to a new investment idea. This approach has often led to long holdings exceeding the one year threshold for long-term capital gains treatment. However, the Fund also capitalizes on the analyst’s expertise regarding these companies by adjusting the size of core holdings or opportunistically entering into positions with shorter expected time horizons.
To provide clients superior risk adjusted returns over a complete market cycle, provide the best customer service possible and to make each client feel like they are our only client.

column8:
LONG-ONLY
Saddle Peak’s investment strategy is value oriented. Saddle Peak seeks to acquire long positions in undervalued companies where, in the opinion of the advisor, the value of the company’s assets and/or earnings power are not accurately reflected by the company’s current market price. Each position entered into is the result of the application of a valuation methodology the advisor uses to arrive at an estimate of the company’s true worth, or intrinsic value. Saddle Peak’s philosophy is to make investments that trade at a steep discount to intrinsic value thus providing both a large margin of safety against a decline in the company’s market price and a superior potential for appreciation. Saddle Peak believes that appreciation over time is best accomplished by minimizing capital loss and it views this “margin of safety” as a critical component to avoiding loss. When opportunities with attractive risk reward characteristics are scarce, the advisor may hold a significant portion of its assets in cash with a view toward preserving capital. A position will generally be closed out when the price approaches intrinsic value.

THE HEDGE
The hedge fund is a long/short equity fund whose assets are invested in an actively managed portfolio of domestic stocks, options, and certain futures interest. The partnership’s portfolio is expected to have a bias toward long positions. However, it may have a short bias at times depending on the assessment of the overall market. Short positions generally will be used for hedging purposes, rather than to capture a price swing or trend to the downside. In addition to short sales, put option on individual companies, market indices or industries may be used to offset the portfolio’s long positions. Although the use of leverage is not contemplated, some leverage may be used on occasion to increase the capacity for investments. 

In each case, Saddle Peak seeks good absolute returns through a focused portfolio of value-oriented, multi-capitalization investments. Saddle Peak will generally not be invested in more than 25 to 30 companies at any one time. Control of risk is constantly measured and positions will generally be closed when the price approaches its target price intrinsic value.

column8:
At Martin Currie, strategic planning is oriented to the overall quality of the firm, with a primary focus on delivering investment excellence. Its aim as an active-equity manager is to deliver consistent, superior returns for clients globally. Martin Currie does this via its client focused range of outcome orientated equity investment solutions based on its four distinct product pillars, Market Aware, Long-Term Unconstrained, Sustainable Income and Growth and Absolute Returns. 

The delivery of investment excellence is central to what Martin Currie offers its clients. This means a clearly-articulated investment proposition: 
Committed to high-conviction active management
Martin Currie’s high-conviction, active management is driven by the rigour of its distinctive and repeatable research process. 
A collaborative and multi-disciplinary approach to research, drawing on the knowledge of colleagues from across the investment floor, enables Martin Currie to identify and evaluate the mispricing of individual stocks – specifically for those companies that it believes will offer sustainable, long-term growth. This in-house research is always complemented by local market research, lateral industry insights, and company meetings. 
Of course, this is not a process in isolation. It is interwoven with a strong valuation discipline based on the forecasting of normalised earnings power, as well as risk, to determine a company’s fair value.
ESG analysis and active ownership are also fully embedded into Martin Currie’s investment process. This allows Martin Currie to engage with investee companies in order to better understand what motivates them and the mechanisms in place for decision-making. 
Overlaying all of this is an independent and dynamic risk function that informs an optimum risk allocation. All portfolios are continuously monitored for correlated, unintended and excessive risk. When market conditions change, the investment risk team provides Martin Currie’s portfolio managers with experienced interpretation of risk models to quantify the likely impact. As such, Martin Currie thinks of its independent risk team as being the representative of its clients within the firm.
The responsibility for the creation and implementation of the firm’s plan sits with the executive committee, chaired by Chief Executive Officer, Julian Ide.

Todd Asset Management (TAM) is a team-oriented firm with a history of experienced, performance-driven management, outstanding client service and high ethical standards. We understand that strong past performance is no guarantee of future performance, and, therefore, constantly strive to identify innovative ways to strengthen our process and improve client returns.

Through its value-oriented predecessors, TAM’s roots can be traced back to 1967. In 1986, TIA adopted its unique methodology using intrinsic value to identify a stock’s true underlying value. Today, with more than 30 years of experience with the methodology, TAM believes Price/Intrinsic Value is still the most effective fundamental tool to determine the true valuation of a stock. The Price/Intrinsic Value philosophy is the foundation of all of the firm's equity strategies. 

Todd Asset Management LLC plans to increase assets under management by at least 20-30% over the next three years. There have been several developments over the past year to both drive and support this growth:

1. We have won several institutional mandates since 6/30/2014 totaling more than $350 million in assets under management.

2. The firm's relationship with Advisors Asset Management, established in 2014, has resulted in TAM strategies being added to a large retail broker dealer platform and is actively generating new accounts. 

3. On July 1, 2014, we launched a new product, International Intrinsic Value Opportunity, with $100 million

4. We launched a commingled product for our International Intrinsic Value strategy that funded during 4Q 2018.

5. The firm started building a third generation portfolio management team in October 2014 with the promotion of Shaun Siers, CFA, from Research Analyst to Portfolio Manager. Jeremy Roane, Research Analyst, was added in October 2016.

In addition, we will continue to cultivate our consultant relationships, sub-advisory opportunities, and respond to RFPs to increase assets.

"Trust & Fiduciary Management Services Inc. has a business strategy based on widespread application of its pioneering development of diversified portfolios of exchange traded pass through securities, i. e. entities which are exempt from federal corporate income tax on the condition that they distribute substantially all of their profits to shareholders. The most widely recognized such entities are Real Estate Investment Trusts (REIT's); Master Limited Partnerships (MLP's); Business Development Companies (BDC's); Royalty Trusts; and Closed End Funds. TFMS believes that this strategy is the most practical and effective means of providing reliable income to investors in the emerging secular bear market for traditional fixed income securities. In addition, the firm provides a variety of other investment styles to support clients' needs for broad diversification in their portfolios.
Income based pass through strategies are offered in both active and passive investment styles. The active management style is called Matrix Income (tm) and has a twelve year GIPS compliant, independently verified track record. It is currently offered in separately managed accounts (SMA's) and in a traditional 1940 Act compliant open end mutual fund. Applications of this style in multi-manager income oriented mutual funds and closed end funds are being pursued. The passive investment style is embodied in the High Income Pass Through Securities (HIPS) 300 Index, calculated for TFMS by S&P Dow Jones. Applications of this index are contemplated in ETF, Index Fund, and private portfolio licensing.

column8:
Our primary business strategy is to grow our business by targeting top tier performance combined with exceptional client service. Client retention is a major focus. Our firm’s goal is to meet or exceed clients’ needs and expectations in all aspects of the client relationship. We continuously reinvest in our investment and client service teams to enhance the client experience. We have a dual strategy to promote new business development: growth within current equity offerings and growth through distribution channels. Along those lines, we have organized our firm to insulate portfolio managers and analysts from business management responsibilities. Our firm is structured into three divisions: investment management, business services, and distribution (sales and service). Business services include legal and compliance, finance, human resources, operations, and facilities management. Distribution includes firm-wide marketing services, as well as institutional and private client distribution. This structure allows investment professionals to concentrate solely on investment management while the services and distribution organizations are able to leverage their capabilities across the enterprise. 

The goal of our research process is to identify candidates for investment that are growth companies with superior earnings prospects. Each Investment Team member serves as a research analyst, and our investment analysts research industry groups in each of the five broad market sectors (consumer, cyclical, financial-services, health-care, and technology). We believe that the benefits of industry-specific research versus product- or capitalization-specific research are significant, as the same analysts maintain coverage of global companies that may migrate from small cap to mid cap, or mid cap to large cap. Industry-specific research ensures that the same personnel follow a security through its lifecycle. The lead portfolio manager collaborates directly with the industry analysts regarding the output of their analysis, and is ultimately responsible for security selection and for the individual weighting of each portfolio holding. 

Our overriding commitment is to provide clients with consistently superior investment management services. Our firm can fulfill this commitment by attracting and retaining employees who are experts in their respective fields. To retain key personnel, our firm provides incentives including higher-than-average base compensation, an attractive benefits package, and performance-based bonuses.

column8: The Ecofin team is comprised of socially minded, ESG-attentive investment professionals that bring significant experience and expertise investing in social impact, sustainable infrastructure, energy transition and water & environment. The investment strategies include public and private as well as debt and equity investments and are accessible through a variety of vehicles and solutions. Ecofin’s strategies seek to achieve positive impacts that align with the UN Sustainable Development Goals by addressing global issues in climate action, clean energy and water, education, healthcare and sustainable communities.

First and foremost, the firm’s overall business strategy is intensely focused on producing above average returns for our investors by generating market returns in “up” markets and outperforming in “down” markets. The firm follows a disciplined private market valuation process that generates buy and sell targets for a defined universe of predictable and understandable businesses. The ability to grow the firm is effectively tied to the capacity of the firm’s investment professionals to generate attractive investment ideas. While the firm does not have a hard ceiling in terms of AUM at this point, its management believes that a doubling of its AUM would not impair its investment results. The firm’s target investment partner account is $1 million and above, in both partnership and separately managed account formats.

column8:
VanEck’s mission is to offer investors forward-looking, intelligently designed investment strategies that take advantage of targeted market opportunities. VanEck’s approach is to think outside the confines of financial markets as they exist today and identify what major historical trends – political and technological – will change the opportunity set of these markets. Being one of the first to offer investors access to international markets in 1955 set the tone for the Firm’s drive to identify and define investment trends.

VanEck’s story evolves with the early identification of asset classes and trends that went on to shape the investment management business: in 1968 with monetary policy and gold, in 1993 with China and emerging markets, and in 2006 with ETFs.

VanEck brings its best to clients through:

-Independence – a history of placing clients’ interests first in all market environments
-Insight – early identification of investment trends and asset classes that investors may be missing
-Accessibility – clients access to portfolio management teams and Firm resources
-Execution – market-tested portfolio management teams and well-designed processes

VanEck seeks to provide clients with timely and informative materials. In additional to standard client reporting packages, VanEck provides: 

-Portfolio and performance updates, market commentary and views on a regular basis
-Quarterly investment strategy reports written by portfolio managers and analysts
-Frequent value-add and educational papers on timely topics and market events
-Video commentary by its portfolio managers on its website www.vaneck.com

Additionally, in-person client meetings or webinars with portfolio managers and relationship managers are available as requested by the client.

The following investment vehicles are available:

-Mutual funds (retail and institutional shares) 
-Pooled institutional funds
-Variable insurance portfolios
-Sub-advisory
-UCITS funds
-Separate accounts
-Limited partnerships
-Exchange Traded Products

column8:
Algorithmic Trading Advisors's objective is tho be the investment manager for retail and institutional clients world-wide.

Our goal is to produce superior investment results through the use of sophisticated genetic networks (artificial intelligence) to accurately predict the FOREX market and proprietary money management to leverage trading opportunities. We have developed an algorithmic program that uses market timing. technical analysis, and numerous indicators to accurately predict FOREX market movement. Using the power of the Internet investment performance is always available at home, at work or on the road.

We are classified as an Investment Club by the National Futures Association (NFA) and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC). The NFA and CTFC are the federal regulators for the Forex market. Our structure, if on the stock equity side, would also be classified as an Investment Club by the SEC.

As an Investment Club we don’t hold investor funds, they are held in a normal bank account. The investor gives us permission to trade their account under a limited power-of-attorney. The investor funds are batched (pooled) for a trade but each investor trade is individual.

Algorithmic Trading Advisors LLC is a Commodity Trading Advisors registered with the NFA and CFTC. A CTA is an individual or organization which, for compensation or profit, advises others as to the value of or the advisability of buying or selling commodity futures. Algorithmic Trading Advisors LLC is also an Introducing Broker (IB). An IB is an individual or organization which solicits or accepts orders to buy or sell commodity futures but does not accept money or other assets directly from customers to support such orders.
